SIMPLE: indolence
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indolence
<hw>In"do*lence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>indolentia</ets> freedom from pain: cf. F.
<ets>indolence</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Freedom from that which pains, or harasses, as toil,
care, grief, etc.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have ease, if it may not rather be called
<qex>indolence</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Bp. Hough.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quality or condition of being indolent;
inaction, or lack of exertion of body or mind, proceeding from love of
ease or aversion to toil; habitual idleness; indisposition to labor;
laziness; sloth; inactivity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Life spent in <qex>indolence</qex>, and therefore sad.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As there is a great truth wrapped up in ⟦ldquo⟧diligence,⟦rdquo⟧
what a lie, on the other hand, lurks at the root of our present use of
the word ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>indolence</qex>⟦rdquo⟧! This is from
⟦ldquo⟧in⟦rdquo⟧ and ⟦ldquo⟧doleo,⟦rdquo⟧ not to grieve; and
<qex>indolence</qex> is thus a state in which we have no grief or pain;
so that the word, as we now employ it, seems to affirm that indulgence
in sloth and ease is that which would constitute for us the absence of
all pain.</q> <rj><qau>Trench.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indolency</ent>⟦br⟧
